SIMPLE: aura
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Aura
<hw>Au"ra</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Aur⟦ae⟧</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>aura</ets> air,
akin to Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any subtile, invisible
emanation, effluvium, or exhalation from a substance, as the aroma of
flowers, the odor of the blood, a supposed fertilizing emanation from
the pollen of flowers, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>The peculiar sensation, as of a
light vapor, or cold air, rising from the trunk or limbs towards the
head, a premonitory symptom of epilepsy or hysterics.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Electric aura</b></col>, <cd>a supposed electric fluid,
emanating from an electrified body, and forming a mass surrounding it,
called the <xex>electric atmosphere</xex>. See <er>Atmosphere</er>,
2.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Aural</ent>⟦br⟧
